# Java Generics

## Core Principles
- Use generics to eliminate unchecked casts and enforce compile-time type safety
- Prefer generic methods over raw types -- never use raw types in new code
- Favor `List<T>` over `T[]` for generic collections (arrays are covariant, generics are invariant)

## Bounded Type Parameters
- `<T extends Comparable<T>>` for ordering constraints
- `<T extends AutoCloseable>` for resource constraints
- Multiple bounds: `<T extends Serializable & Comparable<T>>`
- Recursive type bounds for self-referential types: `<T extends Enum<T>>`

## Wildcards (PECS)
- **Producer Extends**: `? extends T` when reading from a structure
- **Consumer Super**: `? super T` when writing to a structure
- `?` (unbounded) when the type parameter is unused in the method body
- Do not use wildcards in return types -- let callers bind the type

## Type Erasure Awareness
- Generics are erased at runtime: `List<String>` and `List<Integer>` are the same class
- Cannot use `instanceof` with parameterized types (use raw type or pattern matching)
- Cannot create generic arrays: `new T[]` is illegal; use `List<T>` or `Array.newInstance`
- Provide explicit `Class<T>` tokens when runtime type info is needed

## Generic Methods
- Prefer generic methods over generic classes when the type parameter is local to one method
- Use type inference: callers should not need to specify type arguments explicitly
- Static utility methods are natural candidates for generic methods

## Anti-Patterns
- Raw types: `List` instead of `List<?>` or `List<String>`
- Unchecked casts: `(List<String>) rawList` without safety guarantee
- Overusing wildcards in APIs -- use concrete type parameters when the caller needs type flow
- `Comparable<Object>` instead of `Comparable<T>` -- loses specificity

